Stanisław Bohusz Siestrzeńcewicz, or Stanisłaŭ Bohuš-Siestrancevič (Belarusian: Станіслаў Богуш-Сестранцэвіч, 1731–1826) was a Belarusian who became the first [MASK] of the Metropolitan Archdiocese of Mohilev, an Archbishop from 1784 and a prominent member of the Russian Academy (1807), who had earlier converted from Calvinism.
He soon left the Catholic Eastern Rite and, under the guidance of Archbishop Valerian Trifa of the Romanian Orthodox [MASK] of America, converted to Orthodoxy on February 15, 1968.

Leonard Paul Blair (born April 12, 1949) is an American prelate of the Roman Catholic Church serving as the thirteenth [MASK] and fifth and current archbishop of the Archdiocese of Hartford, Connecticut.
On 16 February 1959, he was appointed [MASK] of the Archdiocese of Pescara-Penne and then Archbishop with the name change of the diocese on 2 March 1982.

Daniel Austin Dowling (April 6, 1868 – November 29, 1930) was an American prelate of the Roman Catholic Church who served as the first [MASK] of the Diocese of Des Moines and the second Archbishop of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis.
Dom João Anes (or João Eanes) (died May 3, 1402) was [MASK] (since 1384) and also the first archbishop of Lisbon.

Count Redmond Garrett Prendiville (11 September 1900 in Wood, Kerry, Ireland – 28 June 1968 in Perth, Western Australia), a former Australian metropolitan bishop, was the fifth [MASK] and second Roman Catholic Archbishop of the Archdiocese of Perth.

John Raphael Quinn (born March 28, 1929) is a Roman Catholic [MASK], who is the Archbishop Emeritus of the Archdiocese of San Francisco; he served as the archdiocese's sixth archbishop from 1977 to 1995.

Pietro Bonomo (1458–1546) was an Italian humanist and diplomat, who became [MASK] of Trieste in 1502 and archbishop of Vienna briefly in 1522.

Maroun Elias Nimeh Lahham (born 20 July 1948, Irbed, Jordan), is the first Archbishop of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Tunis from 2010, after having been [MASK] for more than four years.
Erik Benzelius the younger (January 27, 1675 in Uppsala – September 23, 1743) was a priest, theologian, librarian, [MASK] of Linköping, 1731-1742 and Archbishop of Uppsala, Sweden, 1742–1743.
